h\n1 <= n <= 5000\n0 <= citations[i] <= 1000\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def hIndex(self, citations: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def hIndex(self, citations: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Sort the citations in descending order\n        citations.sort(reverse=True)\n        \n        # Initialize h-index to 0\n        h_index = 0\n        \n        # Iterate over the sorted citations\n        for citation in citations:\n            # If the citation count is greater than the current h-index, increment h-index\n            if citation > h_index:\n                h_index += 1\n            else:\n                # If not, we can't increase the h-index further\n                break\n        \n        return h_index\n```\n\nThis solution sorts the list of citations in descending order and iteratively checks how many papers have at least as many citations as the current h-index. The time complexity of this approach is O(n log n) due to the sorting step, and the space complexity is O(1) if we ignore the space used by the sorting algorithm.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}